In [13]:
# Segregating the independent and target columns and performing a train test split
target = signal_data['Signal_Strength']
df = signal_data.loc[:, signal_data.columns != 'Signal_Strength']
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(df,target, test_size = 0.3, random_state = 10)
In [19]:
# performing standard scaling to remove data skewness and to standarize the values
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from pandas import DataFrame
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_test)

In [24]:
regressionModel=Sequential()
regressionModel.add(Dense(128, kernel_initializer='normal',input_dim = X_train.shape[1], activation='relu'))
regressionModel.add(Dense(64, kernel_initializer='normal',activation='relu'))
regressionModel.add(Dense(32, kernel_initializer='normal'))
regressionModel.add(LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1))
regressionModel.add(Dense(16, kernel_initializer='normal'))
regressionModel.add(LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1))
regressionModel.add(Dense(1, kernel_initializer='normal'))
regressionModel.add(LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1))
regressionModel.compile(loss='mean_absolute_error', optimizer='adam', metrics=['mean_squared_error'])
regressionModel.summary()

15/15 [==============================] - 0s 1ms/step - loss: 0.5173 - mean_squared_error: 0.4595
MSE for test scaled data is 0.4595, which is better than that on the unscaled data¶

Pickling the model¶

In [33]:
# Saving the model to disk
def pickleModel(model, model_file_name):
    model.save(model_file_name)
    print("Saved model to disk")
In [34]:
pickleModel(regressionModel,"regressionSignalModel.h5")

In [37]:
classifierModel=Sequential()
classifierModel.add(Dense(128, kernel_initializer='normal',input_dim = X_train.shape[1], activation='relu'))
classifierModel.add(Dense(64, kernel_initializer='normal',activation='relu'))
classifierModel.add(Dense(32, kernel_initializer='normal'))
classifierModel.add(LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1))
classifierModel.add(Dense(16, kernel_initializer='normal'))
classifierModel.add(LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1))
classifierModel.add(Dense(9, kernel_initializer='normal',activation='softmax'))
classifierModel.compile(loss='mean_absolute_error', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])
classifierModel.summary()

In [43]:
classifierDropoutModel=Sequential()    
classifierDropoutModel.add(Dense(50, input_dim = X_train.shape[1] , kernel_initializer='he_normal'))
classifierDropoutModel.add(BatchNormalization())
classifierDropoutModel.add(Activation('relu'))
classifierDropoutModel.add(Dropout(0.2))
classifierDropoutModel.add(Dense(50, kernel_initializer='he_normal'))
classifierDropoutModel.add(BatchNormalization())
classifierDropoutModel.add(Activation('relu'))
classifierDropoutModel.add(Dropout(0.2))
classifierDropoutModel.add(Dense(50, kernel_initializer='he_normal'))
classifierDropoutModel.add(BatchNormalization())
classifierDropoutModel.add(Activation('relu'))
classifierDropoutModel.add(Dropout(0.2))
classifierDropoutModel.add(Dense(9, kernel_initializer='he_normal'))
classifierDropoutModel.add(Activation('softmax'))

adam = optimizers.Adam(lr = 0.001)
classifierDropoutModel.compile(optimizer = adam, loss = 'categorical_crossentropy', metrics = ['accuracy'])

import tkinter as tk;
from tkinter import ttk;
import pandas as pd;
import re;

##App window
win= tk.Tk();
win.title('Neural Networks GUI - Great Learning');


##-------------------------Step1----------
Name= ttk.Label(win,text="Step1:File Name")
Name.grid(row=0,column=0,sticky=tk.W)

Name_var= tk.StringVar();
Name_entrybox= ttk.Entry(win,width=16,textvariable=Name_var)
Name_entrybox.grid(row=0,column=1)

def importData():
    global df
    DF_Name= Name_var.get()
    DB_extension=re.findall("\..*",DF_Name)
    if DB_extension==['.csv']:
        df=pd.read_csv(DF_Name);
    confirm="Done"
    confirm_entrybox= ttk.Entry(win,width=16)
    confirm_entrybox.grid(row=0,column=3)
    confirm_entrybox.insert(1,str(confirm))
    
importDataButton = ttk.Button(win, text="Import Data", command= importData)
importDataButton.grid(row=0,column=2)

##-------------------------Step2----------
Target= ttk.Label(win,text="Step2:Target Column")
Target.grid(row=1,column=0,sticky=tk.W)

Target_var= tk.StringVar();
Target_entrybox= ttk.Entry(win,width=16,textvariable=Target_var)
Target_entrybox.grid(row=1,column=1)

def checkTarget():
    global TARGET
    target_Name= Target_var.get()
    if target_Name in df.columns:
        TARGET= df[target_Name]
        confirm="Found"
        confirm_entrybox= ttk.Entry(win,width=16)
        confirm_entrybox.grid(row=1,column=3)
        confirm_entrybox.insert(1,str(confirm))


    
importTargetButton = ttk.Button(win, text="Import Target", command= checkTarget)
importTargetButton.grid(row=1,column=2)


##-------------------------Step3----------
def trainModel(): 
    global regModel
    regModel=regressionModel;
    confirm_entrybox= ttk.Entry(win,width=25)
    confirm_entrybox.grid(row=4,column=2)
    try:
        regModel.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs = 200, verbose = 1)
        confirm="Network Trained"
        confirm_entrybox.insert(1,str(confirm))  
    except:
        confirm="Exception occured"
        confirm_entrybox.insert(1,str(confirm))  
        
def runModel():  
    scores1= regModel.evaluate(X_test, y_test,  verbose=1)
    print('Accuracy of regression model on test data: {}% \n Error on test data: {}'.format(scores1[1], 1 - scores1[1]))  
    pickleModel(regModel, "regression_signal_GUI.h5")
    confirm="Saved Model to disk"
    confirm_entrybox= ttk.Entry(win,width=25)
    confirm_entrybox.grid(row=5,column=2)
    confirm_entrybox.insert(1,str(confirm))            
             

NNRegressionLabel= ttk.Label(win,text="Step3: Neural Network Regressor")
NNRegressionLabel.grid(row=3,column=0,sticky=tk.W)


RegressionLabel= ttk.Label(win,text="Regression")
RegressionLabel.grid(row=4,column=0,sticky=tk.E)

trainButton = ttk.Button(win, text="Train", command= trainModel)
trainButton.grid(row=4,column=1)


PickleLabel= ttk.Label(win,text="Pickle")
PickleLabel.grid(row=5,column=0,sticky=tk.E)

runButton = ttk.Button(win, text="Run", command= runModel)
runButton.grid(row=5,column=1)


##-------------------------Step4----------

def trainClassifierModel():
    global classificationModel
    classificationModel=classifierDropoutModel;
    confirm_entrybox= ttk.Entry(win,width=25)
    confirm_entrybox.grid(row=7,column=2)
    try:
        classificationModel.fit(X_train_scaled, y_cat_train, epochs = 200, verbose = 1)
        confirm="Network Trained"
        confirm_entrybox.insert(1,str(confirm))  
    except:
        confirm="Exception occured"
        confirm_entrybox.insert(1,str(confirm))  
    
def runClassifierModel():
    scores2=classificationModel.evaluate(X_test_scaled, y_cat_test,  verbose = 1)
    print('Accuracy of categorical model on test data: {}% \n Error on test data: {}'.format(scores2[1], 1 - scores2[1]))  
    pickleModel(classificationModel, "classification_GUI.h5")
    confirm="Saved Model to disk"

    confirm_entrybox.grid(row=8,column=2)
    confirm_entrybox.insert(1,str(confirm))

Design, train, tune and test a neural network image classifier¶

Defining the sequential model with different tunable paramters as input¶
In [68]:
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dense
from tensorflow.keras import regularizers, optimizers

def train_and_test_loop(iterations, lr, Lambda, verb=True):

    # hyperparameters
    iterations = iterations
    learning_rate = lr
    hidden_nodes = 256
    output_nodes = 10
        
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Dense(hidden_nodes, input_shape=(1024,), activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(hidden_nodes, activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(output_nodes, activation='softmax', kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(Lambda)))
    
    sgd = optimizers.SGD(lr=learning_rate, decay=1e-6, momentum=0.9)
    # Compile model
    model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer=sgd, metrics=['accuracy'])
    
    # Fit the model
    model.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=iterations, batch_size=1000, verbose= 1)
    return model
In [69]:
def train_and_test_loop1(iterations, lr, Lambda, verb=True):

    # hyperparameters
    iterations = iterations
    learning_rate = lr
    hidden_nodes = 256
    output_nodes = 10

    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Dense(hidden_nodes, input_shape=(1024,), activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(hidden_nodes, activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(output_nodes, activation='softmax', kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(Lambda)))
    
    sgd = optimizers.SGD(lr=learning_rate, decay=1e-6, momentum=0.9)
    # Compile model
    model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer=sgd, metrics=['accuracy'])
    
    # Fit the model
    model.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=iterations, batch_size=1000, verbose= 1)
    score = model.evaluate(X_train, y_train, verbose=0)
    
    return score

Automating the process of finding the best value of the parameter for the model¶
In [87]:
import math

best_accuracy = 0
best_lr = 0
best_Lambda = 0

for k in range(1,10):
    lr = math.pow(10, np.random.uniform(-3.0, 3.0))
    Lambda = math.pow(10, np.random.uniform(-7,-2))
    best_acc = train_and_test_loop1(100, lr, Lambda, False)
    print("Try {0}/{1}: Best_val_acc: {2}, lr: {3}, Lambda: {4}\n".format(k, 9, best_acc[1], lr, Lambda))
    if (best_acc[1]>best_accuracy) :
        best_accuracy = best_acc[1]
        best_lr = lr
        best_Lambda = Lambda
        
print('\n\nBest parameters of the model :')
print('LR :', best_lr)
print('Lambda :', best_Lambda)
print('Accuracy :', best_accuracy)

def train_and_test_loop2(iterations, lr, Lambda, verb=True):

    # hyperparameters
    iterations = iterations
    learning_rate = lr
    hidden_nodes = 256
    output_nodes = 10
        
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Dense(hidden_nodes, input_shape=(1024,), activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(hidden_nodes, activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(output_nodes, activation='softmax', kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(Lambda)))
    
    sgd = optimizers.SGD(lr=learning_rate, decay=1e-6, momentum=0.9)
    # Compile model
    model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer=sgd, metrics=['accuracy'])
    
    # Fit the model
    history = model.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=iterations, batch_size=1000, verbose= 1 , validation_data=(X_val, y_val))
    return history

best_model = train_and_test_loop2(100, best_lr, best_Lambda)

Plot the training loss, validation loss vs number of epochs and training accuracy, validation accuracy vs number of epochs plot and write your observations on the same¶

In [90]:
# Visualize loss history
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
accuracy_train = best_model.history['accuracy']
accuracy_val = best_model.history['val_accuracy']
plt.plot(accuracy_train, 'r', label='Training accuracy');
plt.plot(accuracy_val, 'b', label='validation accuracy');
plt.title('Training and Validation accuracy');
plt.xlabel('Epochs');
plt.ylabel('Accuracy');
plt.legend();
plt.show();
In [91]:
# Visualize loss history
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
loss_train = best_model.history['loss']
loss_val = best_model.history['val_loss']
plt.plot(loss_train, 'r', label='Training loss');
plt.plot(loss_val, 'b', label='validation loss');
plt.title('Training and Validation loss');
plt.xlabel('Epochs');
plt.ylabel('Loss');
plt.legend();
plt.show();
Observations¶

We see that the model is giving very good accuracy on the train and validation data set. Also from the graph it is clear that the loss and the accuracy on the train and validation dataset is similar which shows that the model have similar performance on the train and validataion dataset. The parameters such as lr and Lambda are identified by automating the process of finding the best values for the same.
